b'' b" \tif my life depended on it, i'd say that it's a scope that" b' \tuses long-persistance phosphor to keep the successive' b' \ttaces on the screen for some unit of time "store" them.' b' \tdo i get to live?' b'' b"we'll let you live, but just this once...." b'' b'there\'s more to a real "storage" scope than just a long-persistence' b"phosphor. actually, the phosphor isn't usually anything special at all;" b'what makes a storage tube work is a screen placed just *behind* the phosphor,' b'which becomes charged as the electron beam intially "writes" the trace.' b'with the trace now written to the screen, a separate low-level "flood"' b'electron gun keeps the image lit by exciting those areas of phosphor' b'which are next to the "written" areas on the storage screen. there are' b'some problems with this the resolution is limited compared to a non-storage' b'tube, and the stored trace tends to "bloom" with time.' b'' b'of course, this is pretty much obsolete technology, done in by the current' b'digital scopes which use raster-scan displays and keep everything in a' b'frame-buffer memory anyways.' b'' b'^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^' b'' b'ah, yes from the same people who brought you that amazing new reading' b'program that\'s sweeping eastern europe: "hooked on consonants!" b'' b'' b'bob myers kc0ew hewlett-packard co. |opinions expressed here are not' b'systems technology div. |those of my employer or any other' 